                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Nergal, stop.<br /><br />For starters I take offense at your stupid googley-eyed smiley-face...not that I expect you care or that I care whether you care or not.  I know you have to isolate all variables to test for Charisma.  The point I was trying to make, ya putz, is that such a test would be useless for anything other than academic debates (maybe you read that part of my post?).<br /><br />Why do I say this?  Suppose Charisma is a factor...does that mean I'll be able to charm mob X if I have Y charisma?  Or is the MR of the mob more of a factor?  Or is the level of the mob more of a factor?  I have my own theories but the point remains that we know level and MR have an effect...and there are a lot of people arguing vehemently over this but I have yet to see a single shred of "evidence".<br /><br />But perhaps you are so limited, mentally, that you cannot handle more than one idea at a time...cannot grasp the idea of looking beyond "does charisma make a difference" towards trying to predict with moderate reliability what mobs we can successfully charm for long periods of time and how much of an effect various strategies affect same (i.e. giving pet -mr gear, getting malo on it prior to charming, getting it tashed prior to charming, equipping opal encrusted steins, etc.).</span id="msg"></font></td>
