                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Ah, this tired argument again.  If you actually go and look at the data that supposedly proves that Charisma has no effect on charm durations, you will see that some of the data is bogus.  It is skewed by some extremely long charms with low charisma.  On of the reported charms exceeds the maximum duration of the spell.  If you exclude just that one charm -- which is indisputably impossible -- then the average charm with high charisma was longer than the average charm with low charisma.<br /><br />But, as I have said before, who cares?  The bonus to duration is tiny (maybe five percent), and the base duration remains random.  Even if you have Charisma 300, you have no guarantee that a charm will last longer than a few seconds.  A five percent bonus to a 10 second charm is .5 seconds.  Woo hoo.<br /><br />Charisma would be valuable if it increased the base duration of a charm in a reliable way.  However, it is indiputable that it DOES NOT work that way.<br /><br />Therefore, we should all be able to agree on the bottom line: regardless of whether you think charisma affects charm duration, it has no functional value in charming.</span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
