                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The point I was trying to make, ya putz, is that such a test would be useless for anything other than academic debates<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">On this, we agree completely (and my wife would probably agree with you on the "putz" part).<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">But perhaps you are so limited, mentally, that you cannot handle more than one idea at a time...cannot grasp the idea of looking beyond "does charisma make a difference" towards trying to predict with moderate reliability what mobs we can successfully charm for long periods of time and how much of an effect various strategies affect same (i.e. giving pet -mr gear, getting malo on it prior to charming, getting it tashed prior to charming, equipping opal encrusted steins, etc.).<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">Whether or not charisma affects charm, and the relative charmability (i.e. magic resistance) of various mobs are completely separate issues.<br /><br />If you are advocating a study of mob charmability, I'm behind you 100%...but (there's always a but isn't there?), you still have to do the testing in a statistically valid way.  Otherwise you just end up with a lot of meaningless numbers.  That means keeping everything except the mob constant...including charisma (just in case it does have an influence).  For best reliability that means running large batches of tests on each individual mob (hopefully keeping mob level consistant for each batch of tests).<br /><br />Since we don't know the actual MR of mobs to use as a baseline, that would still only get us a relative comparison between mobs.<br /><br /><br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
